&lt;p&gt;The 4th Street Food Co-op is a small all-vegetarian natural foods food cooperative store, open to the public.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The 4th Street Food Co-op offers organic produce, locally grown as much as feasible, large selection of bulk goods such as flours, oats, dry fruits, many varieties of rice, dry beans, dry pasta, tofu, health and beauty supplies, and more. You will additionally find other natural food products like soy milk, vegan ice cream, and other packaged foods.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The co-op has managed to replace almost all of the &amp;quot;corporate organic&amp;quot; non-produce produced by companies owned by multinationals not meeting ethical standards.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Anyone can shop at the co-op, but working members receive discounts between 15 and 25% depending on the number of hours they work. Membership is $10 for the first year and $25/year after that.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Atlas Cafe is a tiny cafe with a some vegan/fake-meat sandwiches and wraps, such as a vegan Moroccan chicken crepe and pastrami sandwich.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Atlas recently discontinued some of their vegan offerings, including the fish sticks and philly cheese steak.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;All their deserts are vegan, made by &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.vegguide.org/vendor/view.html?vendor_id=2409&quot;&gt;Vegan Treats&lt;/a&gt; bakery, who deliver weekly to a number of New York restaurants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Atlas has a satellite location, Little Atlas, which serves much of the same food and desert on West 4th Street between Mercer and Broadway.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Vegetarian and Kosher Indian cuisine.  Known for inexpensive buffets.  Specializes in southern Indian as well as Gujarati and Punjabi.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Serves dosas, iddli, and curries.  Has an all you can eat buffet at lunch for $5.95 during weekdays.  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Menu items are clearly labeled if they contain dairy.  Also, spice levels are indicated.  Since they are Indian vegetarians, no need to worry about egg products.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Healthy home made pitas, Kosher, ready to go, Middle-Eastern food. Located at the heart of the East Village of NYC. We serve fresh food, perfect for those looking for a quick, inexpensive (under $5.00) and healthy meal.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Our environment is warm, welcoming, and modern,&lt;br /&gt;
a great spot to sit and comfortably have a bite.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Serving delicious falafel, hummus, and the Chickplant, a special eggplant creation.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Small, elegant dessert bar that serves seasonal ingredients in 3 course prix fixe desserts for $12.  Seats 20 in a clean, open kitchen environment.  A small selection of teas, champagnes, and wine pairings are also offered, as well as coffe.  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You are first given a small spoonful of sweets to cleanse your palate.  Then the three courses are: amuse bouche, entree, and petit fours.  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Does not take reservations on weekends.    Closed on Mondays.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This place makes their own tofu, made by experienced grandmothers.  They are aware of the differences between vegetarian and vegan, and will ask if you are able to eat eggs when you order meatless entrees.  Also, ask for vegeterian Ban Chan (small side dishes) w/o any fish or meat.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Ya- Chae Cham- Doo- Boo, which is vegetable tofu stew, is made vegan.  This is highly unusual in Korean cooking, which has a tendency to use anchovy stock in almost all casseroles.  Specify if you want it to be spicy, and they will comply and make it spicy (no dumbing down for non-Koreans).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Do not eat any red Kim Chee.  It cannot be guaranteed safe unless you speak with the person who has made it.  If it is a cold clear soup with white turnip, then it is vegan.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Dimple is a south Indian restaurant in Midtown offering breakfast and lunch specials, a lunch buffer between 11:15 and 3PM, and other specials all day. The restaurant offers plenty of seating, but little decor.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dimple offers a wide selection, with almost any south Indian dish you&#39;ve heard of - dosas, idli and vada, samosas, biryani, rice and curry dishes, and traditional Indian breads.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A lunch buffet is offered every day except Sunday for $8, and several lunch take out specials are offered as well. The average meal will cost you less than $10.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Most dishes, unless specifically named &amp;quot;butter&amp;quot; or &amp;quot;cheese&amp;quot;, are vegan, although it is always wise to ask. They also have a selection of sweets in a deli case, although few are likely to be vegan.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;They have more than a dozen brands of beer, including 7 Indian brands.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;All the food is certified kosher by Rabbi Leonard Bronstein.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dimple has a second location in Jackson Heights, Queens, as well.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Gobo was recently opened by the sons of New York&#39;s famous Zen Palate owners. While Zen Palate is alcohol-free, Gobo has a great selection of beer and wine. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The food is absolutely superb. The best way I can describe it is asian-influenced gourmet vegan food.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The atmosphere is nice, although it can get a bit noisy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Call 212.255.3242 for delivery and take-out.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Health Conscious Express is an Ital caf&eacute; and juice bar in the East Village. The store&#39;s motto is that healthy food can be delicious.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The food is mostly quick sandwiches, such as soy or tofu burgers, and 3 empanada-like patties including one made of ackee. They also have deserts, raw and not, and a wide selection of juices, smoothies, and health shots.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the deli case they have some grocery items, including organic fruit and even vegenaise. There is also a display of herbal tinctures in the corner.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Everything is vegan except for the yogurt.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;They have an additional, larger location with more grocery items in Lorelton, Queens.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Swanky organic restaurant that caters to veg*ns and carnivores alike.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Many of the appetizers, entrees and pasta dishes are prepared dairy-free, and they also offer a number of vegan desserts.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Grains, beans and flour are certified organic.  Produce is organic when available and economical.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Swanky organic restaurant that caters to veg*ns and carnivores alike on the Upper West Side.  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Appetizers, entrees and pasta dishes are prepared dairy-free.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Grains, beans and flour are certified organic.  Produce is organic when available and economical.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Prix Fixe available.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Aside from honey in certain items, the food at this Seventh Day Adventist eatery is all vegan. Food is served buffet style and for $3.99, you get a plate and bowl you can fill it up to your heart&#39;s content. Fresh-baked desserts are extra but are still reasonably priced, about $1 each.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The buffet has a big salad bar with various beans, vegetables, and dressings, and there is a hot bar with a number of vegetables, rice, and tofu-based dishes. You can also purchase a la carte items, including veggie burgers, nachos, sandwiches, and salads.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It can be tough to find the place unless you know what you&#39;re looking for. You enter a huge office building on Broadway then walk down a flight of stairs and you&#39;ll find the restaurant. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The dining area is absolutely huge (and underutilized), and there are both mini booths and tables. The decor is pretty plain, but given the lunch price, it&#39;s reasonable.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Breakfast buffet from 7:30am-10am. Lunch buffet from 11:30am-3:30pm (or until food runs out).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That&#39;s right - an entirely vegan shoe shop, that also sells a few t-shirts, bags and stuff.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Most of their stock is from the UK, but even if you&#39;re from Britain, it&#39;s still worth a visit, for the sheer pleasure of being able to buy &lt;em&gt;anything&lt;/em&gt; in the shop!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;They also have a couple of very sweet cats.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;NY Dosas, commonly called simple &amp;quot;Dosa Man&amp;quot;, is an all-vegan street cart at the corner of Sullivan Street and Washington Square South on NYU&#39;s campus.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A masala dosa with sambar and coconut chutney is $4. Other varieties of dosas are offered, as well as a curry with fake meat, samosas for $1, and vegan chicken drumsticks for $1.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dosa Man is usually there Monday through Saturday, 11 until 4, although some days he doesn&#39;t show up and other days he runs out of food and closes early.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Organic Harvest Cafe is dedicated to providing you with the highest quality and best tasting organic foods in New York City. While the majority of our menu is prepared for a vegan diet (no dairy and no animal products) in mind, we are very excited to introduce alternatives such as fish or chicken, it is 100% vegan.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;At Organic Harvest we provide 100% certified organic foods. Our food is prepared in the finest all-clad stainless steel pots and pans. Even the healthiest food cooked in improper cookware can have deleterious long term health consequences. We cook with the finest cooking oils which possess the highest smoking points so as to prevent carcinogens from entering your food. In your hands right now is the most diverse and creative health oriented menu in all of New York City. All of our menu items are prepared from scratch daily. We offer delicious soups, appetizers, salads, sandwiches, wraps, burgers and entrees. A glorious selection of wheat free, dairy free and sugar free desserts are also available daily. We carry the finest nutritional supplements to complement our smoothies and our juices will provide you the extra burst of energy you&#39;ve been seeking.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Whether health is already a high priority in your life or you are looking to make a positive change, we&#39;re happy to serve you! I promise you&#39;ll love it!!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Pongal is a south Indian restaurant in Midtown offering lunch and dinner specials. They are Kosher certified and they boast &amp;quot;freshly prepared&amp;quot; food so plan on waiting 20-25 minutes for your meal.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;They offer a wide selection, with almost any south Indian dish you&#39;ve heard of - dosas, idli and vada, samosas, biryani, rice and curry dishes, and traditional Indian breads.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;They don&#39;t offer a lunch buffet but they do offer lunch specials, many of which are vegan. Most dishes, unless specifically named &amp;quot;butter&amp;quot; or &amp;quot;cheese&amp;quot;, are vegan, although it is always wise to ask.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Pongal is a south Indian restaurant in Midtown offering lunch and dinner specials. They are Kosher certified and they boast &amp;quot;freshly prepared&amp;quot; food so plan on waiting 20-25 minutes for your meal.&lt;/p&gt;
